\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator considered the application and found that the programme meets minimum requirements for all the relevant criteria. The evaluator questions the WIL component in the programme\'2C but recommends that the programme is accredited with a single condition. As this is a public institution\'2C criteria 3\'2C 4\'2C 7 and 8 do not require completion and the conditions related to these criteria do not apply.\line \line The Bachelor of Laws \'28LLB\'29 is designed to equip well-rounded law graduates to enter the legal profession\'2C to engage in careers that require the application of law\'2C and to pursue postgraduate studies in law. The proposed programme is in line with the above-stated mission of the institution in that\'2C as stated in the application\'2C it will contribute to reconstruction and development of society by offering diverse\'2C quality academic and community outreach programmes which are morally and culturally relevant.\line \line The programme is a professional Bachelor\'E2\'80\'99s degree that comprises 512 credits. Students complete the programme over four years full-time study\'2C and exit at NQF Level 8. The curriculum is designed to facilitate progression from NQF Level 5 to NQF Level 8. The evaluator indicated that the programme design meets minimum requirements. The Directorate notes that the module descriptors in Criterion 1 provide limited programme information\'2C but the institution provided all the module information with Criterion 5.\line \line The Directorate notes that the institution assigned 10\'25 of learning time to Work-Integrated Learning \'28cf. Section 1.5 \'E2\'80\'93 experiential learning\'2Fworkplace-learning\'29. However\'2C in section 1.10\'2C the application states that the programme does not include WIL. The institution should clarify the WIL component of this programme\'2C and review sections 1.5 and 1.10 accordingly.\line \line The evaluator commented on the budget and staff allocation in Criterion 1. Also\'2C the evaluator indicated that the programme needs improvement in terms of staffing \'28Criteria 3 \'26 4\'29 and questions the omission of supporting documentation for specifically criterion 3. Note that public institutions sign a declaration and are not required to provide information on staffing \'28Criteria 3 \'26 4\'29 or infrastructure and systems \'28Criterion 7 \'26 8\'29.\line \line The evaluator indicated that articulation is appropriate. The programme allows for vertical articulation to a Master of Laws\'2C or cognate qualifications. Also\'2C it allows for horizontal articulation to a BCom\'28Law\'29 or BA\'28Law\'29.\line \line The admission and selection criteria adhere to current legislation and are commensurate with the programme\'E2\'80\'99s academic requirements. Admission via Recognition of Prior Learning \'28RPL\'29 is subject to the institutional RPL policy and process.  \line \line The Bachelor of Laws will be delivered as a contact programme\'2C and the learner-centred teaching and learning methodology supports the institutional strategy for teaching and learning. Face-to-face lectures are supported by online learning. The learning material will be made available on the WiseUp\'2FBlackboard and in the library. The evaluator notes that lecturers will use PowerPoint presentations as a teaching aid to assist students in their learning activities such as simulation\'2C role play\'2C small group discussions and providing feedback.\line \line The institution uses established institutional systems and mechanisms are in place to monitor student progress\'2C evaluate the programme and improve or maintain the quality of the programme. Also\'2C the institution has the policy structure\'2C processes and capacity in terms of systems\'2C structures\'2C policies\'2C procedures and processes for materials design\'2C development and delivery of this programme. \line \line Assessment is subject to the Institutional Examinations Policy. Assessment at the institution is said to be focused on applied competencies and evidence thereof will include\'3A assignments\'2Ftasks and examinations\'2C providing evidence of the ability to apply knowledge to practice\'2C oral presentations that will be observed in context to assess the ability to communicate with comprehension. The evaluator indicated that\'2C at the programme and modular level\'2C assessment will be systematically and purposefully used to generate data for formative \'28e.g. providing timeous feedback to inform teaching and learning\'29 as well as for summative purposes \'28grading\'2C ranking\'2C selection\'2C predicting\'29.\line \cell \pard 

